{
  "What does mechanical advantage tell you about a simple machine?": "",
  "How much the machine multiplies your input force": "",
  "How quickly the machine can complete a full cycle": "",
  "How much electrical energy the machine consumes": "",
  "How many moving parts the machine contains inside": "",
  "Mechanical advantage is the ratio of output force to input force. It tells you how much the machine multiplies the force you put in.": "",
  "A machine with a mechanical advantage of 4 means the output force is how many times the input force?": "",
  "2 times the applied input force": "",
  "8 times the applied input force": "",
  "4 times the applied input force": "",
  "6 times the applied input force": "",
  "A mechanical advantage of 4 means the machine produces an output force that is 4 times greater than the input force applied.": "",
  "What is the formula for mechanical advantage?": "",
  "Input force divided by input distance": "",
  "Output force divided by input force": "",
  "Input force divided by output force": "",
  "Output force multiplied by input force": "",
  "Mechanical advantage (MA) is calculated as output force divided by input force: MA = F_out / F_in.": "",
  "If a machine has a mechanical advantage greater than 1, what does it do?": "",
  "It decreases the output force compared to input": "",
  "It produces equal output and input forces exactly": "",
  "It increases the output force compared to input": "",
  "It eliminates the need for any input force at all": "",
  "A mechanical advantage greater than 1 means the machine multiplies the input force, producing a larger output force.": "",
  "What is the trade-off when a machine increases force through mechanical advantage?": "",
  "You must apply force over a greater distance": "",
  "The machine becomes completely frictionless": "",
  "You must use a much heavier machine overall": "",
  "The machine needs an external power source": "",
  "When a machine multiplies force, you must apply that force over a longer distance. This is the fundamental trade-off of simple machines.": "",
  "What is the mechanical advantage of a machine that uses 20 N of input force to lift a 100 N load?": "",
  "3": "",
  "5": "",
  "2": "",
  "4": "",
  "MA = output force / input force = 100 N / 20 N = 5. The machine multiplies the input force by a factor of 5.": "",
  "What is the ideal mechanical advantage of an inclined plane?": "",
  "Height of the ramp divided by the base length": "",
  "Base length multiplied by the height of the ramp": "",
  "Length of the ramp divided by its height": "",
  "Height of the ramp multiplied by the ramp length": "",
  "The ideal mechanical advantage of an inclined plane equals the length of the slope divided by the height: IMA = length / height.": "",
  "Why is the actual mechanical advantage of a machine always less than the ideal mechanical advantage?": "",
  "Because gravity acts differently on each machine type": "",
  "Because friction and other real-world losses exist": "",
  "Because machines always double the input force applied": "",
  "Because ideal calculations include extra safety factors": "",
  "Friction and other energy losses in real machines reduce the actual output force, making the actual MA less than the ideal MA.": "",
  "A pulley system with 3 supporting ropes has an ideal mechanical advantage of what value?": "",
  "6": "",
  "1": "",
  "9": "",
  "For a pulley system, the ideal mechanical advantage equals the number of rope segments supporting the load. With 3 supporting ropes, the IMA is 3.": "",
  "A machine with a mechanical advantage less than 1 is designed to increase what?": "",
  "The total amount of force produced by the machine": "",
  "The speed or distance of the output movement": "",
  "The weight that the machine is able to support": "",
  "The efficiency rating of the machine being used": "",
  "A machine with MA less than 1 trades force for speed or distance. It does not multiply force but instead increases the speed or distance of movement.": "",
  "What is mechanical advantage?": "",
  "The ratio of the output force produced to the input force applied": "",
  "The total amount of energy a machine stores in its structure": "",
  "The speed at which a machine completes one full work cycle": "",
  "The maximum weight that a machine can safely support overall": "",
  "Mechanical advantage is the ratio of output force to input force. It measures how much a machine multiplies the force you apply.": "",
  "What does the term 'ideal mechanical advantage' mean?": "",
  "The average mechanical advantage measured in repeated trials": "",
  "The mechanical advantage calculated assuming no friction exists": "",
  "The highest mechanical advantage ever recorded for a machine": "",
  "The mechanical advantage measured under maximum load conditions": "",
  "Ideal mechanical advantage is the theoretical value calculated without friction. It represents the best possible performance of the machine.": "",
  "What is efficiency in the context of simple machines?": "",
  "The percentage of input work that is converted to useful output work": "",
  "The total amount of force that a machine can produce at its maximum": "",
  "The number of moving parts contained within the machine's structure": "",
  "The speed at which the machine performs a given amount of work done": "",
  "Efficiency is the ratio of useful output work to total input work, expressed as a percentage. It tells you how much work is lost to friction and other factors.": "",
  "What does the term 'input force' mean when discussing machines?": "",
  "The force that the machine exerts on the object being moved": "",
  "The force that a user applies to operate the machine": "",
  "The force of gravity acting on the machine's own weight": "",
  "The frictional force generated inside the machine parts": "",
  "Input force (also called effort force) is the force that a person or motor applies to operate the machine. It is the force you put into the system.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'output force' in simple machines?": "",
  "The frictional force that resists the movement of a machine part": "",
  "The force exerted by the machine on the load or resistance": "",
  "The force required to initially start the machine from rest state": "",
  "The force that holds the machine in place during its operation": "",
  "Output force (also called resistance force or load force) is the force the machine exerts on the object it is working on, such as lifting a heavy load.": "",
  "What does 'work input' mean for a machine?": "",
  "The product of the output force and the output distance": "",
  "The product of the input force and the input distance": "",
  "The total kinetic energy of all moving machine parts": "",
  "The amount of energy lost to heat through friction forces": "",
  "Work input is the work done by the user on the machine. It equals the input force multiplied by the distance over which that force is applied.": "",
  "What is a compound machine?": "",
  "A machine that operates without any friction or energy loss at all": "",
  "A machine that is made up of two or more simple machines combined": "",
  "A machine that has a mechanical advantage of exactly one or higher": "",
  "A machine that can only be powered by an electrical energy source": "",
  "A compound machine is a device that combines two or more simple machines. Examples include scissors (lever + wedge) and a bicycle (wheel and axle + lever + gears).": "",
  "What does 'effort distance' mean in the study of machines?": "",
  "The distance the load moves when the machine is operated": "",
  "The maximum range over which the machine can function well": "",
  "The distance over which the input force is applied to the machine": "",
  "The total length of the machine measured from end to end overall": "",
  "Effort distance is the distance over which the input force (effort) is applied. When a machine multiplies force, the effort distance is greater than the load distance.": "",
  "What does 'load distance' mean when analyzing a simple machine?": "",
  "The distance over which the effort force is applied to the machine": "",
  "The distance the load or resistance moves due to the machine": "",
  "The total weight of the object that is placed on the machine": "",
  "The height of the machine above the ground reference level used": "",
  "Load distance (also called resistance distance) is the distance the load moves when the machine operates. In a force-multiplying machine, this distance is shorter than the effort distance.": "",
  "What does 'actual mechanical advantage' mean?": "",
  "The mechanical advantage measured in a real machine that includes friction effects": "",
  "The mechanical advantage that exists only in theoretical calculations and formulas": "",
  "The mechanical advantage of a machine that has been lubricated and well maintained": "",
  "The mechanical advantage determined by the manufacturer label on the machine itself": "",
  "Actual mechanical advantage is the MA measured from a real machine during operation. It accounts for friction and is always less than the ideal mechanical advantage.": "",
  "Maya uses a 3-meter ramp to push a box up to a platform that is 1 meter high. What is the ideal mechanical advantage of this ramp?": "",
  "IMA of an inclined plane = length / height = 3 m / 1 m = 3. The ramp multiplies Maya's pushing force by a factor of 3.": "",
  "Carlos lifts a 200 N box using a pulley system with 4 supporting ropes. Approximately how much force does he need to apply?": "",
  "About 100 N of pulling force": "",
  "About 200 N of pulling force": "",
  "About 50 N of pulling force": "",
  "About 800 N of pulling force": "",
  "With 4 supporting ropes, the IMA is 4. Force needed = 200 N / 4 = 50 N. Carlos only needs about 50 N to lift the 200 N box.": "",
  "A cyclist pedals a bicycle where the pedal gear has 48 teeth and the rear gear has 16 teeth. What is the mechanical advantage of this gear combination?": "",
  "Gear MA = number of teeth on driven gear / number of teeth on driving gear = 48 / 16 = 3. The gear system provides a mechanical advantage of 3.": "",
  "Aisha uses a crowbar that is 60 cm long. She places the fulcrum 10 cm from the end under a heavy rock. What is the ideal mechanical advantage?": "",
  "IMA of a lever = effort arm / load arm = 50 cm / 10 cm = 5. The effort arm is 60 - 10 = 50 cm, giving an IMA of 5.": "",
  "A construction worker uses a machine to lift a 500 N load, applying only 125 N of force. However, the ideal mechanical advantage is 5. What is the efficiency of this machine?": "",
  "90%": "",
  "80%": "",
  "75%": "",
  "85%": "",
  "AMA = 500/125 = 4. Efficiency = (AMA/IMA) x 100 = (4/5) x 100 = 80%. The machine loses 20% of its work to friction.": "",
  "Two ramps lead to the same 2-meter-high platform. Ramp A is 4 meters long and Ramp B is 8 meters long. Which ramp requires less force to push a box up, and why?": "",
  "Ramp A, because shorter ramps are always more efficient overall": "",
  "Ramp B, because a longer ramp has a greater mechanical advantage": "",
  "Both require the same force since both reach the same height": "",
  "Ramp A, because it has a steeper slope which multiplies force more": "",
  "Ramp A: IMA = 4/2 = 2. Ramp B: IMA = 8/2 = 4. Ramp B has a higher MA, so it requires less force but you push over a longer distance.": "",
  "Jamal wants to pry open a paint can lid. He tries using a short screwdriver and then a long screwdriver as levers. Why does the longer screwdriver work better?": "",
  "Because the longer handle increases the effort arm and mechanical advantage": "",
  "Because the longer screwdriver is made of a stronger metallic material": "",
  "Because the longer screwdriver has more friction on the paint can lid": "",
  "Because the longer screwdriver weighs more and adds extra downward force": "",
  "A longer screwdriver increases the effort arm. Since IMA = effort arm / load arm, a longer effort arm gives a greater mechanical advantage, making it easier to pry.": "",
  "Emma lifts a flag on a flagpole using a single fixed pulley. She pulls down with 30 N of force to raise the 30 N flag. What is the mechanical advantage, and what benefit does the pulley provide?": "",
  "MA is 2; the pulley doubles the force she applies to the rope": "",
  "MA is 1; the pulley changes the direction of force, not its size": "",
  "MA is 0; a single fixed pulley provides no advantage whatsoever": "",
  "MA is 3; the pulley triples her applied force through leverage": "",
  "A single fixed pulley has an MA of 1 -- it does not multiply force. Its advantage is changing the direction of force, letting Emma pull down to lift the flag up.": "",
  "A delivery worker pushes a 600 N package up a 6-meter ramp to a 1.5-meter loading dock. If the worker pushes with 200 N of force, what is the efficiency of the ramp?": "",
  "65%": "",
  "IMA = 6/1.5 = 4. AMA = 600/200 = 3. Efficiency = (AMA/IMA) x 100 = (3/4) x 100 = 75%. Friction accounts for the remaining 25% energy loss.": "",
  "A student designs a compound machine by combining a lever (MA = 3) with a pulley system (MA = 2). What is the overall mechanical advantage of the compound machine?": "",
  "5, because you add the two individual mechanical advantages together": "",
  "3, because the lever's mechanical advantage is the one that dominates": "",
  "6, because you multiply the individual mechanical advantages together": "",
  "2, because the pulley's mechanical advantage is the one that dominates": "",
  "The overall MA of a compound machine is found by multiplying the MAs of the individual simple machines: 3 x 2 = 6. The compound machine multiplies force by a factor of 6.": ""
